New York Green Taxi Data Analysis

05 Jun 2018

New York Taxi Data Analysis¶

Introduction¶

In this analysis, I will be analysing the New York Taxi Data for Green Taxi.

Data used is from Sept, 1st 2015 to Sept, 30th 2015. Green Taxi: Started in 2013, to serve outer-borough commuters. Therefore, Green Taxis are not allowed to make pickups in Lower Manhattan, Upper East Side and JFK and LaGuardia Airport. So most of the trips of Green Taxi starts from Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens and Bronx. This will be quite visible when we will be looking at scatter plot of pickup locations.

Furthermore, even though Green Taxis are not allowed to pick passengers from Lower Manhattan but there is no restrictions in drop location. Again this will be evident when we look at scatter plot of Dropoff locations, and see that all 4 big Boroughs of NY are covered in Dropoff location including Lower Manhattan.

For the analysis, I have divided into following sections:¶

1. Cab Pickup¶

  • Analysis on location of pickup
  • Trip Count Analysis

2. En Route analysis¶

  • Trip Distance
  • Trip Speed

3. Cab Dropoff¶

  • Analysis on location of drop off
  • Fare Analysis

4. Airport Rides Analysis¶

5. Machine Learning Model to Predict Tip Percentage¶

  • Analyse which predictors are best in predicting Tip percentage.

6. Visualization of Intra and Inter-Borough Rides¶

Data Cleaning¶

  • As we see above that all the values in column ‘Ehail_fee’ are missing. Therefore, I will drop the Ehail_fee’ column from the dataframe.
  • Along with that, there are only 4 missing values in ‘Trip_type’ column I can just remove those rows.
  • I found few outliers in many columns and since their count is low as compare to the size of data and there is no pattern in missingness, I have decided to remove them too.
In [8]:
# Dropping 'Ehail_fee' column because it doesn't has any value
df.drop(['Ehail_fee'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Remove rows with Trip_type values as 'NA'
df = df[~df.Trip_type.isnull()]


# Calculating Trip duration
df['Trip_duration'] = (df.Lpep_dropoff_datetime - df.lpep_pickup_datetime).dt.seconds/3600

# removing outliers
column_cutoff = dict({'Trip_distance':(0, 30), 
                      'Fare_amount':(0, 150), 
                      'Tip_amount':(0, 20), 
                      'Tolls_amount':(0, 15), 
                      'Total_amount':(0, 150),
                      'Trip_duration':(0.0001,np.inf)})

for column, cutoff in column_cutoff.items():
    df = df[df[column].between(cutoff[0], cutoff[1])]
    
df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

4. Airport Rides Analysis¶

Link: http://www.nyc.gov/html/tlc/html/passenger/taxicab_rate.shtml

From above link, I found that trips with ‘RateCodeID’ equal to 2 and 3 are JFK airport and Newark Airport rides respectively. Since Green Taxis are not allowed to pickup passengers from any Airport we can assume that all trips with RateCodeID 2 and 3 are all going to Airport and NOT coming from airport.

Note: There is no special code for LaGuardia Airport Trips

The final rate code in effect at the end of the trip.

  1. = Standard rate
  2. = JFK
  3. = Newark
  4. = Nassau or Westchester
  5. = Negotiated fare
  6. = Group ride

Since Green Taxi are not allowed to Pickup from Airports, therefore only rides with RateCodeID equal to 2 and 3 are the ones going to Airport from outer boroughs.

5.Machine Learning Model to Predict Tip as percentage of Total Fare¶

5.1 Creating a derived variable for tip as a percentage of the total fare.¶

Since we have trips where total_amount is zero, and to avoid error while calculating percentage tip, I’m replacing zero with 0.001 value, which is negligible in terms of money

In [26]:
df['Total_amount'] = np.where(df.Total_amount == 0, 0.001, df.Total_amount)
df['percentage_tip'] = 100.0 * df.Tip_amount/df.Total_amount

5.2 Defining Predictors and Target Variable¶

Thing to notice is that we should not include ‘Tip Amount’ or ‘Total Amount’ to Predict the tip percentage of total fare. Otherwise it will be data leakage from predictors to response variable.

In [27]:
predictors = ['VendorID', 'Store_and_fwd_flag', 'RateCodeID', 'Passenger_count', 
              'Extra', 'MTA_tax', 'improvement_surcharge', 'Payment_type', 'Trip_type',
              'Trip_distance', 'Fare_amount', 'Tolls_amount', 
              'Pickup_longitude', 'Pickup_latitude', 'Dropoff_longitude', 'Dropoff_latitude', 
              'pickup_borough', 'dropoff_borough','pickup_weekday']

label = ['percentage_tip']

5.3 Spliting the data into training, validation and testing dataset¶

In [28]:
np.random.seed(seed=SEED)

# Generating RANDOM indices for split
indices = np.random.permutation(df.shape[0])

# Defining data size
training_size = 100000
validation_size = int(0.2 * training_size)
testing_size = int(0.2 * training_size)

# Creating indices for training, validation, and testing dataset
train_idx = indices[:training_size]
validation_idx = indices[training_size:training_size+validation_size]
test_idx = indices[training_size+validation_size:training_size+validation_size+testing_size]

# Creating 3 dataframes: Train, Validation, and Test
df_train = df.iloc[train_idx]
df_validation = df.iloc[validation_idx]
df_test = df.iloc[test_idx]

5.4 Label Encoding Categorical column¶

In [29]:
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'
categorical_column = ['Store_and_fwd_flag', 'pickup_borough', 'dropoff_borough','pickup_weekday']

le = dict()
for column in categorical_column:
    # Defining LabelEncoder object for Categorical data
    le[column] = LabelEncoder()
    
    # Fitting and transforming the categorical data with LabelEncoder
    df_train.loc[:,column] = le[column].fit_transform(df_train[column])
    
    # Using the same LabelEncoder(Fitted With Training data) to transform validation and test dataset
    df_validation[column] = le[column].transform(df_validation[column])
    df_test[column] = le[column].transform(df_test[column])

5.5 Best Model Fit¶

Below is final model I’m using for predictions.

Even though I’m just using 30 trees in Random Forest model, more tree seems to be improving the performance. Also, I’m only using 100k data set to train the model, 20k to validate and 20k for testing.

I’m only 100K data points for training due to limitation of computation capability of my machine. But given better performing machine, more data can be used to potentially increase the performance of the model.

These are the values of hyperparameters of my final model.
{'n_estimators': 30 'max_depth': 10 'bootstrap': True, 'max_features': 'auto' 'min_samples_leaf': 2 'min_samples_split': 3 }

With these model hyperparameters I’m getting very similar performance on all three dataset: Training, Validation, and Testing. Since model performance on Training and Validation dataset is very similar, we can be sure that there’s no Overfitting.

In [30]:
# Creating Model object

In [31]:
# Function to check Performance
def performance_check(model, df): 
    """
    Function takes trained model and data and returns
    RMSE and MAE of predictions
    """
    # Predictions
    y_predict = model.predict(X= df.loc[:, predictors])

    # Calculating Error on Predictions
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true=df.percentage_tip, y_pred=y_predict))
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true=df.percentage_tip, y_pred=y_predict)

    print('RMSE: {:.2f} | MAE {:.2f}'.format(rmse, mae))
    return rmse, mae
In [32]:
metric = list()
print('Performance on Training Data: ',  end='')
metric.append(performance_check(model, df_train))
print('Performance on Validation Data: ', end='')
metric.append(performance_check(model, df_validation))
print('Performance on Test Data: ', end='')
metric.append(performance_check(model, df_test))
metric = np.array(metric)

Important Predictors¶

  • Payment Type is the most important predictors. The reason for this that 100% all tips come from rides where passenger paid the fare using Credit card. Therefore, payment type gives the indication whether passenger is going to pay the tip or not.

  • Fare Amount is good indicator because people generally prefer to make Tip as some percentage of their Fare. This percentage usually ranges from 10% to 20%. So model is able to pick this pattern.

  • Pickup and Dropoff Locations are the rest of the best predictors, which makes sense because passengers getting from high end places such as Manhattan might tend to give more tip than others. In below analysis you will see that passenger a Green Taxi from Queens is usaully less likely to pay Tip.

Summary of Above Visualization we can say:¶

  • New Yorkers travelling in Green Taxi Cab for Intra-borough are from Brooklyn.
  • New Yorkers Travelling in Green Taxi Cab for Inter-borough starts from Brooklyn and goes to Manhattan particularly in Lower Manhattan.
  • Most of the Green Taxi coming to JFK, LaGuardia and Newark Airport comes from outside borough.

Further Analysis¶

  • For this analysis, I have removed lot of cases where Total Amount, Tip, Fare etc were less than zero. I’m not sure why this is the case. We need to look into why this is happening.
  • Just looking at one month of data i.e. Sept, 2015 could be create bias. Just one month of ride data might not be representative. Further analysis should be done on whole 1 year of data to ensure to capture any seasonality or any other time component.
